	(355, 1, '2015-03-07 07:41:50', '2015-03-07 07:41:50', '<?php echo get_template_directory_uri(); ?>/\r\n<body id="indices" class="page page-id-15 page-parent page-template page-template-page-indices-php win8 chrome chrome-0">\r\n<section class="intro-image" style="background-image: url(&#39;<?php echo get_template_directory_uri(); ?>/images/cki-template11-headers-indicies.jpg&#39;);">\r\n                <header>\r\n                    <h1>Constructing the Quality of Life Measures</h1>\r\n                    <hr>\r\n                </header>\r\n            </section>\r\n            <div id="content">\r\n                <div class="row">\r\n                    <a name="constructing-the-indices"></a>\r\n                    <section class="post standard">\r\n                        <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                            <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2 id="contstructing_the_indices">Constructing the Measures</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                            </header>\r\n                            <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <p>Drawing on a long literature, beginning with ancient Greek philosophical works and ending with modern economic and psychological empirical studies, the Quality of Life Project defines Wellbeing and Quality of Life as consisting of two parts: happiness, understood as the range of positive feelings stretching from contentment to joy that a person experiences at any given time, and life satisfaction, understood as a cognitive evaluation of one’s life as a whole. Additionally, the Project found that personal wellbeing derives largely from two broad sources: livability, the external factors that inhibit or enable Quality of Life, and life ability, the internal capabilities that allow individuals to take advantage of their environment.</p>\r\n                                <p><strong>Issues of Data-availability across countries does that the Quality of Life Measures capture livability slightly better than they capture life ability.</strong></p>\r\n                            </article>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </section>\r\n                    <a name="statistical-analysis"></a>\r\n                    <section class="post standard">\r\n                        <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                            <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <h2 id="statistical_analysis">Statistical Analysis</h2>\r\n                                <hr>\r\n                            </header>\r\n                            <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <p>The literature review and empirical meta-analysis identified an initial set of recurring variables found to impact happiness and life satisfaction (see the Project’s literature reviews here). A Principle Component Analysis of approximately one hundred variables in the World Values Survey was used to identify the underlying attributes of these factors. The complete set of factors identified through this analysis was incorporated in an Ordinary Least Squares regression controlling for other factors. The regression analysis revealed a set of variables with a significant positive impact on Quality of Life Measures. These findings were subjected to several forms of sensitivity analysis. The significant factors and controls were grouped together in six dimensions according to their weights and theoretical considerations to form the six dimensions of Quality of Life </p>\r\n                            </article>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </section>\r\n                    <a name="creating-and-validating-the-dimensions"></a>\r\n                    <section class="post standard">\r\n                        <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                            <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <h2 id="creating_and_validation_the_dimensions">Creating and Validating the Dimensions</h2>\r\n                                <hr>\r\n                            </header>\r\n                            <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <p>The six dimensions WERE RECONSTRUCTED using a combination of self-reported and what the academic literature terms objective indicators to correct for the disadvantages of each. The specific indicators were chosen based on statistical analysis, previous findings in the literature, comparability across time and geographical areas, availability, and source reputation in order to ensure the highest possible level of quality. Because previous research has found that outcomes relative to expectations are strong predictors of Quality of Life, changes in some variables were selected in addition to actual levels.</p>\r\n                                <p>The indicators selected were tested analytically through the methods of Confirmatory Factor Analysis, Average Variance Extracted, and the Cronbach’s Alpha method.</p>\r\n                                <p>Indicators were normalized using an approach modeled on the original Human Development measurements. Goalposts were chosen to represent the maximum and minimum values for each indicator, either from the source or from an analysis of the existing observations. Individual scores were calculated using a linearization between the two goalposts. Once the scores for indicators were obtained, they were aggregated hierarchically, with each score equaling either the score of the associated indicator or the average of the scores one level below it. The score for Dimension 1 is therefore the average of the score for Components 1A and 1B while the score for Component 1A is the average of the score for Subcomponents 1Ai and 1Aii.</p>\r\n                                <p>Additional research and analysis relative to the project can be found <a href="<?php echo home_url(); ?>/research">here</a>.</p>\r\n                            </article>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </section>\r\n                </div>\r\n                <a name="dimensions"></a>\r\n                    <section class="carousel dimensions">\r\n        <div class="row">\r\n            <header class="title-group">\r\n                <h2 id="six_dimensions">The Six Dimensions of Quality of Life Measures</h2>\r\n                <hr/>\r\n                <p>\r\n                    The Quality of Life Measures compiled data from a whole host of sources to compose this United States measurements. Various sources include (but are not limited to) the U.S. Census, the Bureau of Labor Statistics, Gallup, and the National Center for Educational Statistics.\r\n                </p>\r\n            </header>\r\n\r\n            <div class="slide-toggle clearfix">\r\n                <a href="#" class="us selected">U.S. Measurements</a><a href="#" class="world">World Measurements</a>\r\n            </div>\r\n\r\n            <ul class="slide-list">\r\n                <li class="slide us">\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns opportunity">\r\n                            <h3>Opportunity</h3>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Poverty<br />\r\n                                Employment<br />\r\n                                Community Vitality<br />\r\n                                Education</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns health_and_environment">\r\n                            <h3>Health &#038; Environment</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                        